le","fullItemName":"Scenario: Varicocele"},{"id":"42465c6c-cc4f-563f-b631-849c7330a5fb","slug":"hydrocele","fullItemName":"Scenario: Hydrocele"}]},{"id":"54eca506-beb4-5707-9686-73ad11c9500d","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"9b67969f-fc26-5cac-b61d-05a832131aad","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"c7a76cc1-2479-5219-948a-de6fd1df394c","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"5bb65ffb-d88a-57bd-afa4-34a94eadaeb1","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"bd50fb8b-903a-5e6d-a9ae-4e8f6ae9b3f8","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"33cc43a6-9f1d-5245-968d-5e59759b5cb9","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"81104ab4-a95d-5ecf-bdcc-24e0a1b8a3cd","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"2dc88556-8fc4-51f7-8e4e-0590678dd6fb","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"487587a8-13ea-5ad1-b569-493005013fa2","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"d5fa2b7a-bbf5-50dc-a503-378f5fcfd881","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field ccdc0e36-4f39-464a-8f94-0e4b5f08c4dc --><h3>How should I manage a man or boy with haematocele?</h3><!-- end field ccdc0e36-4f39-464a-8f94-0e4b5f08c4dc -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 544dd195-d2ac-414e-b5e8-b49e275726da --><!-- begin field a8837aec-b188-4ebb-983f-13e96016472f --><ul><li>If the haematocele follows acute trauma, admit immediately.</li><li>If the haematocele does not follow trauma or is chronic, refer for urgent ultrasound of the scrotum.<ul><li>Small haematoceles (smaller than three times the size of the contralateral testis) can be managed conservatively.</li><li>For large haematoceles surgery is often required, as non-operative management often fails.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field a8837aec-b188-4ebb-983f-13e96016472f --><!-- end item 544dd195-d2ac-414e-b5e8-b49e275726da -->","subChapters":[{"id":"c54ea613-6465-5cef-b8ec-81bda6b6a748","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-38c","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 7e6607c0-1f14-4cbf-9189-d8ceb780c99d --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 7e6607c0-1f14-4cbf-9189-d8ceb780c99d -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 38c20e69-efe1-4043-b689-de8c347e7bb2 --><!-- begin field 826ef1a6-b7de-4832-be83-723fe1a8e2e1 --><p>These recommendations are based on the European Association of Urology guideline <em>Urological trauma</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">EAU, 2016d</a>], and low-quality evidence from case series [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Schuster, 1982</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Schaffer, 1985</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Cass and Luxenberg, 1988</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Kratzik et al, 1989</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Altarac, 1994</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">Chandra et al, 2007</a>] that immediate ultrasound of the scrotum or surgical exploration is indicated to exclude testicular torsion, exclude or repair rupture of the testis, or evacuate a haematocele and prevent the need for later orchidectomy.</p><ul><li>Patients with large haematoceles have a higher rate of orchiectomy than patients who undergo early surgery, even in non-ruptured testes [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">EAU, 2016d</a>].</li><li>Early surgical intervention results in preservation of the testis in more than 90% of cases compared to delayed surgeries which result in orchiectomy in 45-55% of patients [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/scrotal-pain-swelling/references/\">EAU, 2016d</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field 826ef1a6-b7de-4832-be83-723fe1a8e2e1 --><!-- end item 38c20e69-efe1-4043-b689-de8c347e7bb2 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}